Suppose you share your project on GitHub. Another person can clone your project and run:

pip install -r requirements.txt

Then all needed packages get installed.

main.py              -> program starting point
requirements.txt     -> packages needed
README.md            -> project explanation
src/                 -> actual project code
tests/               -> test files
.venv/               -> virtual environment


The core idea:

def main():
    print("Program started")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

means: Define the program logic inside main(), and run it only when this file is executed directly.

pip means: Install external Python packages.

Virtual environment means: Keep project packages separate.

requirements.txt means: List of packages required to run the project.

Project folder structure means: Keep code organized instead of putting everything in one file.

Reliable imports mean: Use proper folder-based imports and run from the project root.